 I apologize for the confusion. Here is an example of a valid XML file that conforms to the schema and includes the GeoJSON file as a reference:
```php
<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<Mission xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance">
    <MissionInformation>
        <MissionName>Farm Corner Tree Photography</MissionName>
        <TaskDescription>Take pictures of trees at the four corners of the farm.</TaskDescription>
    </MissionInformation>
    <Tasks>
        <Task id="1">
            <TaskName>Photograph tree at corner 1</TaskName>
            <TaskLocation>[120.42307592599273,37.36636077337479]</TaskLocation>
        </Task>
        <Task id="2">
            <TaskName>Photograph tree at corner 2</TaskName>
            <TaskLocation>[120.42303004014194,37.366300703749474]</TaskLocation>
        </Task>
        <Task id="3">
            <TaskName>Photograph tree at corner 3</TaskName>
            <TaskLocation>[120.42304700637999,37.36635640370881]</TaskLocation>
        </Task>
        <Task id="4">
            <TaskName>Photograph tree at corner 4</TaskName>
            <TaskLocation>[120.42298051393493,37.36628908556382]</TaskLocation>
        </Task>
    </Tasks>
</Mission>
```
Please note that the TaskLocation element contains a GeoJSON-formatted string representing the GPS location of the tree to be photographed. You can replace this with the actual GeoJSON file if you have one. 